<h4>Tardiness:</h4>
If you are <i>late</i> for an exam, come anyway; I might be able to
accommodate you, provided that you arrive before the end of the exam
period.
<h4>Withdrawal:</h4>
<ul>
  <li>The deadline to <b>drop</b> this course is <u>January 25th</u>.
  (It will not show up on your transcript in that case.)
  <li>You may <b>withdraw</b> from this course at any time before
  <u>March 25th</u>. (The class will be listed on your transcript with
  a grade of W.)
</ul>
Both are done by the student through the Registrar; the instructor cannot drop or withdraw students (although he would appreciate being notified of the withdrawal).  Incompletes are only given in rare circumstances.
<h4>Extra Credit:</h4> The only extra credit available in class is the
occasional extra credit problem on an exam or homework set.  I do not
accept extra credit projects, papers, etc.  (However, there is plenty
of normal credit available in class.)
<h4>Talk to me!</h4> If you run into difficulty with the material, if an unexpected emergency comes up which makes it hard to come to class or complete assignments, if you don't like the way I'm teaching: please tell me.  I will do all that I can to help, within the framework of fairness to your fellow students.  Generally speaking, <i>the earlier I know about a problem, the more I can do to help.</i>
</div>

<h3 class="ongoing"><a name="Grading">Grading</a></h3>
<div class="section">
<ul>
  <li><h4>Homework (20%)</h4>
  Weekly homework will be posted on <b>Mondays</b> on the class website, and collected the following Monday in class (unless otherwise specified).  Homework is due by the end of class for full credit; late homework will be accepted through the following class for half credit <i>unless prior arrangements are made.</i> (It never hurts to ask.)  The two lowest homework grades will be dropped.  Depending on my whim that week, I might grade all problems in complete detail, or I might grade one or two problems at random, or I might give you credit for completing the work.
  <li><h4>Quizzes (20%)</h4>
  Weekly ten-minute quizzes will be given at the beginning of class on
  <b>Fridays</b>, on material covered since the previous quiz.
  Quizzes cannot be made up, though they may be excused for valid
  reason (see above). The two lowest quiz grades will be dropped.
  <li><h4>Midterms (2 x 20%)</h4>
  Two midterms will be given in class.  They are closed-book and
  closed-notes, but students are permitted two sheets of paper, on
  which they may write or print or type or draw anything they choose,
  front and back.  Calculators are permitted (nay, required).  The
  exact dates are to be determined, but the first exam will occur
  sometime <b>after February 22nd</b>, and the second will be <b>April
  4th</b>.  Midterm dates are flexible, and I am happy to take
  requests (e.g. to avoid a big exam or project in another class).

<li><h4>Final Exam:</h4> The two-hour final exam will be held on <b>Friday, May 6th</b> from 10:15-12:15,
    in MH2002.  The final exam will be <i>open book</i> and <i>open
    notes</i>, and will be comprehensive, with an emphasis on the
    material not covered on the previous two exams.
    <li><h4>Honors</h4> If you are enrolled in the "honors section" of this class (section 091), there will be a required project in order to receive honors status; it will not affect your course grade.  Details will be provided to you during the third week of class.
</ul>
